                <pb n="1"/>
            <p>New York&#44; March 6&#47;88<lb/></p>
            <p>Dear Dr.<lb/></p>
            <p>The following is a list of<lb/> the subjects studied in the lower class<lb/> of the Seminary up to date.<lb/>
                &#40;1&#41; 16 chapters of Genesis have been<lb/> read with the commentary of &#91;Hebrew&#93;<lb/> and with thorough grammatical and<lb/> logical analysis and such historical<lb/> and antiquarian excursive as the text<lb/> required.<lb/>
                &#40;2&#41; 40 Psalms have been taken in a<lb/> thorough &#38; logical exegetical manner<lb/> &#38; with full explanation of the syn&#45;<lb/>&#45;tactical &#38; poetic peculiarities.<lb/>
                &#40;3&#41; The history of the Judges and the reign<lb/> of Saul and the first part of the reign<lb/> of David has been <hi rend="underline">thoroughly</hi> taught<lb/> and in this connection the books of<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="2"/>
            <p>the Judges &#38; Samuel I and 8 chapter of<lb/> Samuel II have been read in the original.<lb/>  
                &#40;4&#41; In Grammar the entire system of<lb/> the noun and the verb <hi rend="underline">both regular</hi><lb/> <hi rend="underline">and irregular</hi> have been taken.<lb/>
                &#40;5&#41; In the Mishna the entire treatise<lb/> of &#91;Hebrew&#93; and 9 chapters of &#91;Hebrew&#93; have been<lb/> carefully read with the commentary of<lb/> Bertinora<lb/>
                &#40;6&#41; In the Talmud seven double pages<lb/> of Bala Metzia have been read with<lb/> the commentary of &#91;Hebrew&#93;<lb/> &#34;A complete idea of the work &#40;of this<lb/> class&#41; cannot&#44; however&#44; be gained by the<lb/> mere reading of the afore set table.<lb/>  It will be better understood when it is stated that<lb/> it has arrived at laying a solid foundation<lb/> upon which to erect the future edifice of<lb/> substantial Jewish learning.  Young<lb/> as the<del>y</del> boys are&#44; they <del>boys</del> are nevertheless so thoroughly<lb/> acquainted with the Hebrew&#44; that it is<lb/> almost <del>a plaything in their hands</del> household words with them.<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="3"/>
            <p>They can at once analyse any form<lb/> and with a sound <del>knowledge</del> understanding of the<lb/> Bible and a thorough grounding in<lb/> the history of Israel and a <del>system&#45;</del><lb/><del>&#45;atic and</del> methodical <del>treatment</del> knowledge of Mish&#45;<lb/>&#45;na &#38; Talmud&#44; they possess the true<lb/> basis for a becoming Jewish savants&#44; and are<lb/> reasonably certain&#44; when they graduate&#44;<lb/> <del>&#40;at the end of their seven years&#41; course&#41;</del> to<lb/> rank high among the learned of our<lb/> people and to be <del>thoroughly</del> perfectly capable Rabbis.<lb/>  The spiritual side of their training<lb/> has not been neglected either&#44; <del>and</del> the<lb/> greatest efforts are made to inspire<lb/> them with sincere religious feelings&#44;<lb/> with reverence for our past and devotion<lb/> to the cause of our people.&#34;<lb/></p>
            <p>Concerning the higher class but little<lb/> can as yet be said.  Hebrew Grammar<lb/> and Exodus&#44; by myself&#44; Talmud Chullin thoroughly<lb/> and Berachoth cursorily by Dr Lieberman.<lb/>  The instruction has an advanced<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="4"/>
            <p>character different from the manner in<lb/> the lower class which is more elementary.<lb/>  Hoping that this information will<lb/> cover your requirements&#44; I remain<lb/> sincerely yours<lb/> Bernard Drachman<lb/></p>
            </body>
